label.value: Hodgkin's Disease, Nodular Sclerosis, Lymphocyte Depletion

value.value: Peripheral blood lymphocytes (PBL) transfected to express MOv have been designed for possible use in autologous adoptive cellular immunotherapy of ovarian adenocarcinomas that overexpress folate-binding protein. MOv-PBLs express MOv-gamma (MOv), a chimeric receptor gene product derived from a recombinant gene encoding the variable region of murine monoclonal antibody MOv18 against folate-binding protein (FBP), often overexpressed in human ovarian cancer cells, and the human gene encoding the IgG and IgE Fc receptor gamma subunit. Autologous vaccination with these PBLs stimulates a host cytotoxic T lymphocyte response against ovarian cancer cells that overexpress FBP. (NCI04)

label.value: Malignant Non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma, Small Cleaved Cell

value.value: An adenocarcinoma arising from the intrahepatic or extrahepatic bile ducts.
A carcinoma arising from the intrahepatic or extrahepatic bile ducts.
Primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the endometrium (mucous membrane that lines the endometrial cavity).
A nevus characterised by the presence of excessive pigment.

A rare, slow-growing, usually non-invasive intraepithelial adenocarcinoma affecting the penile skin or mucosal surface. The malignant cells are large with abundant pale cytoplasm and vesicular nuclei with prominent nucleoli. (WHO 2016)
Ureter carcinoma that has spread to another anatomical site.
A urethral carcinoma that has spread to another anatomical site.

A vaccine consisting of myeloma-specific immunoglobulin conjugated to keyhole limpet hemocyanin (KLH), an immune stimulant, with potential antineoplastic activity.  Vaccination with myeloma Ig Id-KLH conjugate vaccine may stimulate the host immune system to mount a cytotoxic T lymphocyte (CTL) response against myeloma cells, resulting in decreased tumor growth. (NCI04)
An antiquated term referring to non-Hodgkin lymphomas with a diffuse architectural pattern.
An antiquated term that refers to a morphologic variant of non-Hodgkin lymphoma which is composed predominantly or exclusively of large neoplastic lymphocytes.
An antiquated term that refers to a non-Hodgkin lymphoma composed of diffuse infiltrates of large, often anaplastic lymphocytes.
A carcinoma that produces mucin.

label.value: Malignant Lymphoma by Cell Type (Working Formulation)
Stage IIIC Breast Cancer AJCC v6

value.value: Stage IIIC Breast Cancer was added in the 6th Edition AJCC Staging Manual, on the basis of metastasis to the infraclavicular lymph nodes (N3) plus any T, M0.

label.value: Invasive Breast Carcinoma by Histologic Grade

value.value: A cancer vaccine consisting of a mixture of a murine lymphoma-derived idiotype and interleukin-2 (IL-2) encapsulated in dimyristoylphosphatidylcholine liposomes.  The use of a liposomal carrier confers immunogenicity to the naturally non-immunogenic idiotype. (NCI04)
A well differentiated invasive breast carcinoma.
A moderately differentiated invasive breast carcinoma.
A poorly differentiated invasive breast carcinoma.

Epithelial dysplasia that develops in Barrett esophagus. It is classified as low or high grade. When technical reasons make the interpretation of atypia difficult, atypia is present but it is not quite to the level of dysplasia, or atypia is present at the bases of the crypts but does not reach the surface of the crypts, then the diagnosis of Barrett esophagus-indefinite for dysplasia is made.

label.value: Low Grade Dysplasia in Barrett Esophagus

value.value: A finding indicating the presence of Barrett esophagus in which the crypts are preserved or mildly distorted.  There is nuclear elongation, mild pleomorphism and loss of polarity, mucin depletion, and increased number of mitotic figures.

label.value: High Grade Dysplasia in Barrett Esophagus

value.value: A finding indicating the presence of Barrett esophagus in which there is marked nuclear pleomorphism and loss of polarity, increased number of atypical mitotic figures, and crypt budding, branching, and crowding.
Persistent inflammation of the superficial portion of the gastric mucosa.  It is a condition that predisposes to the development of ulcer and mucosa-associated lymphoid tissue lymphoma.

A high-grade, aggressive adenocarcinoma arising from the endometrium. It is characterized by the presence of complex papillary patterns with cellular budding. Atypical mitoses, necrosis, and psammoma bodies may be present. It is classified as type II endometrial carcinoma and it is not associated with endometrial hyperplasia. It tends to invade deeply into the myometrium and spreads into the lymphatic vessels. Patients frequently present with spread of the tumor beyond the uterus at the time of diagnosis. The prognosis is usually poor.

An endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising from the endometrium. Morphologically it is characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells containing glycogen vacuoles which are usually subnuclear and reminiscent of early secretory endometrium.

A synthetic peptide derived from the tumor suppressor protein p53 with potential use in cancer immunotherapy.  p53:264-272 peptide consists of amino acid residues 264 through 272 of the p53 protein. Vaccination with this agent may induce a cytotoxic host immune response to tumor cells. (NCI04)

label.value: Endometrial Endometrioid Adenocarcinoma with Small Glands, Tubules or Cords
Endometrial Endometrioid Adenocarcinoma with Metaplastic Changes
Endometrial Endometrioid Adenocarcinoma with Clear Cell Change

value.value: A morphologic variant of endometrioid adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of large multinucleated clear cells.

label.value: Endometrial Endometrioid Adenocarcinoma with a Poorly Differentiated Carcinomatous Component

value.value: A primary endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of a component with poorly differentiated carcinoma cells.

label.value: Endometrial Endometrioid Adenocarcinoma with an Undifferentiated Carcinomatous Component

value.value: A primary endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of a component with undifferentiated malignant cells.
A primary endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of numerous finger-like villi lined by neoplastic columnar cells.

label.value: Endometrial Endometrioid Adenocarcinoma with Small Nonvillous Papillae

value.value: An endometrioid adenocarcinoma arising from the endometrium, in which ciliated cells line the majority of the malignant glands.
A primary endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of eosinophilic malignant glandular epithelial cells.

A paclitaxel formulation containing paclitaxel incorporated in biodegradable polyphosphoester (PPE) polymer form with potential antineoplastic activity. Upon intraperitoneal delivery, paclitaxel PPE microspheres slowly and continuously dissolve and deliver paclitaxel to the tumor site, where it binds to tubulin and inhibits the dynamics of disassembly-assembly of microtubules. As a result, this formulation induces cell cycle arrest and leads to cell death.

label.value: Endometrial Endometrioid Adenocarcinoma with Spindled Epithelial Cells

value.value: A primary endometrioid adenocarcinoma of the endometrium characterized by the presence of spindled malignant epithelial cells.
An infectious process caused by a human papillomavirus. This infection can cause abnormal tissue growth.
